messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /login

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- No

Acceptable methods (based on the code)
- HEAD: No
- POST: Yes
- OPTIONS: Yes
- TRACE: No
- GET: No
- PUT: No
- DELETE: No
- PATCH: No

Explanation
- The login handler is declared with @RequestMapping(value = "/login", method = RequestMethod.POST) in DefaultController, so POST /login is explicitly supported.
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping on DefaultController, so the endpoint path is exactly "/login" (no extra prefix).
- An explicit OPTIONS handler exists: @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.OPTIONS, value = "/*"). The "/*" pattern matches top-level paths such as "/login", so OPTIONS /login is served by that handler and returns HTTP 204 (NO_CONTENT).
- No handler for GET (or for HEAD, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, TRACE) is defined for "/login" in the code. Per the instruction, we do not rely on implicit behavior (e.g., automatic HEAD-from-GET by the framework); therefore HEAD is reported as not supported here.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false because there is no catch-all mapping that allows every method for /login; only the explicit POST mapping and the OPTIONS handler apply.
